// ============================================================
//  ABSTRACTION — Interview Cheat Sheet
// ============================================================
//
//  Q: What is Abstraction?
//  A: Showing only the WHAT (what an object does) and hiding
//     the HOW (how it does it internally).
//     Define a contract/interface — let implementations vary.
//
//  Q: WHY do we need it?
//  A: Three reasons:
//
//     1. SIMPLICITY FOR THE CALLER
//        → sendAlert(service, recipient, msg) works for any
//          notification type. The caller doesn't deal with
//          SMTP config, Twilio keys, Firebase tokens, etc.
//        → Like driving a car — you steer, you don't rewire
//          the power steering mechanism each time.
//
//     2. EXTENSIBILITY WITHOUT MODIFICATION
//        → New notification type (WhatsApp)? Create a new class,
//          implement the abstract method. Done.
//        → You NEVER touch existing working code.
//        → No if-else chains growing forever.
//
//     3. LOOSE COUPLING
//        → Your business logic depends on the ABSTRACTION
//          (NotificationService), not on concrete classes.
//        → You can swap Email for SMS without the caller knowing.
//        → Makes testing easy — pass a MockNotification in tests.
//
//  Q: Abstract Class vs Interface?
//  A:
//     ABSTRACT CLASS                  INTERFACE
//     → Has shared code + abstract    → Pure contract (pre-Java 8)
//       methods                       → Can have default methods
//     → Single inheritance only         (Java 8+)
//     → Use when subclasses share     → Multiple inheritance allowed
//       common behavior               → Use when unrelated classes
//     → "is-a" with shared logic        share a capability
//                                     → "can-do" contract
//
//     WHEN TO USE WHICH:
//     → If you have shared logic (like our validation + logging
//       in send()), use abstract class.
//     → If you just need a contract with no shared logic,
//       use interface.
//     → In real projects, you often use BOTH:
//       Interface → Abstract Class → Concrete Class
//
//  Q: Real-world analogy?
//  A: TV Remote.
//     → You press "Volume Up" (abstraction — the WHAT)
//     → You don't know if it uses infrared, Bluetooth, or
//       WiFi internally (the HOW)
//     → Manufacturer can change IR to Bluetooth — you still
//       just press the same button.
//
//  Q: How is Abstraction different from Encapsulation?
//  A: This is a VERY common interview question!
//
//     ENCAPSULATION              ABSTRACTION
//     → Hides DATA               → Hides IMPLEMENTATION
//     → private fields +         → abstract class / interface
//       controlled methods
//     → "Don't touch my          → "Don't worry about how
//        internals directly"        I do it, just tell me
//                                   what to do"
//     → Works at FIELD level     → Works at CLASS/METHOD level
//     → About PROTECTION         → About SIMPLIFICATION
//
//     They work TOGETHER:
//     → Abstraction hides complexity at the design level
//     → Encapsulation hides data at the implementation level
//
// ============================================================
